<TITLE> 'Govt can't fight graft without media's help' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 19 (bdnews24.com)The media has a pivotal role to play in the fight against corruption, said the information minister and the editor of a leading daily paper on Thursday. Information minister Abul Kamal Azad emphasised the need for government to work together with media and civil society to combat corruption in Bangladesh. "Historically media has played a significant role in every national event  I am confident that media will play the same role in Bangladesh's fight against corruption," Azad said, , addressing a conference on 'Role of media in anticorruption reform efforts'. He added that the government cannot fight "this national enemy" without support from media. In the keynote address, editor of The Financial Express Moazzem Hossain said: "Journalism is more than reporting and writing stories." "Combating corruption presents a daunting challenge everywhere in today's world. This is all the more so in developing countries like Bangladesh where corruption is systemic and embedded institutionally." "Free and responsible media have a vital role to play in the fight against corruption," he said. The conference also heard from discussants Hameeda Hossain, a prominent human rights lawyer, and journalist Abed Khan. Guests included USAID mission director in Bangladesh Denise Rollins and Dhaka University vice-chancellor Prof AAMS Arefin Siddique. Organised by PROGATI, a US-funded project for promoting governance, accountability and transparency, the programme was held at the Westin Ho
